<TEXT>
a bomb exploded sunday night near a bookstore 
injuring three pedestrians and police said a telephone caller 
linked the blast to the campaign against salman rushdies novel 
the satanic verses 
they said they received an anonymous telephone warning about the 
bomb 10 or 15 minutes before it went off in londons west end 
detective chief superintendent derek wilson of scotland yards 
antiterrorist squad said the telephone caller mentioned rushdies 
book which has angered moslem fundamentalists around the world who 
claim it blasphemes their religion 
wilson said the explosion on the sidewalk on great marlborough 
street was near a window of a store that had a display of books but 
the satanic verses was not among them 
an ambulance service spokesman said a woman suffered leg injuries 
and shock and two men also suffered shock he said the victims were 
taken to university college hospital where officials reported they 
were in satisfactory condition 
an independent radio news reporter at the scene said the blast 
was next to a penguin bookstore 
the satanic verses was published last year under the viking 
imprint which is part of the penguin group the company received 
death threats against its staff after the islamic campaign began and 
two london bookstores one specializing in penguin books were 
damaged in arson attacks on april 9 
suddenly there was a huge bang said tracy ryan 23 who was 
looking in a store window across the street when the bomb went off 
it was really frightening and the pavement shook it was a 
terrible bang 
the main store of libertys a textile fashion firm established 
in 1875 is on regent street around the corner from the bomb site 
terry norman a scotland yard spokesman said there appears to 
be no structural damage to libertys or any other shop most firms 
in the area are closed on sundays 
an islamic group in lebanon claimed last month that a man who 
accidentally blew himself up in a london hotel on aug 3 was 
constructing a bomb to attack rushdie 
rushdie has been in hiding under police guard since irans late 
religious leader ayatollah ruhollah khomeini said last february it 
was the duty of a faithful moslem to kill rushdie 
the authors american wife marianne wiggins said a week ago 
that she could no longer stand the strain and had left her husband 
four weeks earlier 
</TEXT>
