the old man smoothes his blue uniform 
shirt and snaps to attention as a visitor approaches the 
fortresslike workers militia headquarters 
asked how long he has been a militiaman jozsef szerepi smiles 
broadly since the beginning he says 
established by the communists as the iron fist of the party a 
year after soviet tanks crushed the 1956 hungarian revolution the 
militia was for years the pride of the men who fought to defend 
communism 
but as hungary prepares for the first free parliamentary 
elections since the communists consolidated power in 1947 the 
militia is under orders from the communist party to transform itself 
into an apolitical force 
political opposition groups question whether it can do so 
warning darkly that the 60000member militia could take to the 
streets to keep the communists in power should they lose in the june 
elections 
on the other side of the ideological spectrum some hardline 
communist militiamen complain bitterly of being betrayed both by 
the party and by their organization 
although the organization makes much of its role in providing 
emergency help in floods fires and other natural calamities it 
remains identified with the soviet submachine gun that forms the 
centerpiece of its emblem 
a may survey of 700 hungarians showed that between 77 percent and 
84 percent of those polled favored the militias dissolution 
after endorsing the concept of multiparty democracy earlier this 
year the hungarian communist party announced may 8 that it no 
longer would control the militia 
militia officials say they are trying to reorganize into a force 
that would take orders only from the government even a future 
noncommunist government but its a daunting task 
for more than three decades militiamen have been required to 
swear allegiance to the red flag of the international workers 
class and to be prepared to give their lives to protect the 
