<TEXT>
the german town of dresden and the english city 
of coventry were officially enemies but their grim eerily similar 
fates during world war ii have drawn them together on the 50th 
anniversary of the beginnng of the great conflict citizens of both 
cities gathered for church services that were joined by a radio 
linkup to recall their towns flaming destruction a half century ago 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
once the jewel of germany because of 
its magnificent architecture dresden virtually burned to death a 
halfcentury ago 
for two days allied aircraft relentlessly bombed the city 
killing tens of thousands of people 
in a solemn church service on sunday dresden recalled the 
firebombing and the germans own destruction of coventry england 
fifty years to the day after britain entered the war the people 
and clergy of two cities spoke to each other via radio hookup and 
shared their flaming pasts 
we in dresden and you in conventry we killed each others 
people and we destroyed each others cities rev christof ziemer 
told about 400 worshipers inside the kruezkirche lutheran church and 
500 others listening to his remarks inside coventry cathedral 
we germans are not minded to shake off the burden of our 
guilt but you have forgiven he told his british listeners via 
british broadcasting corp hookup 
