<TEXT>
americans overwhelmingly favor an increase in the 
federal minimum wage even though most workers are generally 
satisfied with their pay a national poll has found 
nearly nine in 10 respondents to the media generalassociated 
press poll wanted the hourly miniumum raised from 335 and 
twothirds of them favored the 455 minimum approved by congress 
but vetoed by president bush in june 
at the same time six in 10 supported bushs proposal for a 
training wage under which new workers could be kept at 335 for 
their first six months on the job congress has not adopted that 
plan 
on other workplace issues this labor day nearly four in 10 
respondents said they would join a labor union at their workplace 
even though most regarded management more favorably than they viewed 
unions 
most workers gave favorable ratings to their salaries job 
conditions and time off the survey found but pensions were a sore 
point and more than a third were unhappy with their pay 
in a gallup poll meanwhile most fulltime american workers said 
they were satisfied with their jobs twentyeight percent said they 
were completely satisfied with their job and 60 percent said they 
were mostly satisfied while 3 percent said they were completely 
dissatisfied 
many of the 1163 adult respondents to the media 
generalassociated press poll saw unions as weakening and few 
objected to that trend still 49 percent said workers are better 
off with a union while 31 percent disagreed 
overall 47 percent said they were unwilling to join a union 
while 37 percent said they would join one seven in 10 favored 
socalled righttowork laws which ban mandatory union membership 
and while 44 percent had a favorable opinion of unions 64 percent 
thought favorably of management 
rating their own circumstances at work respondents gave top 
grades to the safety of their workplace 87 percent said excellent 
or good and overall working conditions with 81 percent favorable 
nearly seven in 10 were happy with their time off 61 percent 
rated their health benefits favorably and 60 percent said their 
salary was excellent or good as opposed to fair or poor 
pension benefits received the lowest ratings of those with an 
opinion just 46 percent viewed their pension plans favorably while 
41 percent were dissatisfied a quarter called their pension 
benefits poor 
but benefits were not the prime concern fiftyfour percent said 
they would prefer better wages to better benefits just 15 percent 
said their salaries were excellent 
whitecollar management employees were less concerned with 
wages seven in 10 rated their salaries favorably compared with 57 
percent of bluecollar workers and of nonmanagement white collar 
workers 
while 83 percent of union members said that workers are better 
off with unions 46 percent of management employees said that 
workers are better off nonunionized 
southerners also were more dubious of unions they divided about 
evenly on the question more than half of the respondents ages 1829 
and those over 64 said workers are better off with unions 
union membership declining over the years now accounts for just 
under 17 percent of the workforce 
among respondents who are not union workers now 38 percent in 
the youngest group ruled out joining a union that rose to about 50 
percent of the older groups 
fortythree percent overall said unions are getting weaker and 
just 15 percent said they are getting stronger still 33 percent 
said unions are too strong while 20 percent said they are too weak 
the poll was conducted by telephone in july it had a margin of 
error of plus or minus 3 points for all respondents and 4 points for 
the 812 who were employed full time or part time 
the gallup poll also was conducted in july it questioned 697 
adults employed full time and had a 4point margin of error 
