national zoo officials are turning their hopes 
for a successful panda cub birth to next year following the death 
of female panda linglings fifth cub from an infection 
the unnamed male cub died sunday after 39 hours of fighting the 
infection transmitted from its mother zoo officials said 
although lingling is 20 years old the oldest panda surviving 
in any zoo there have been cases in china where pandas older 
lingling have given birth said zoo director michael robinson 
behaviorally lingling has shown every indication of being an 
excellent mother robinson said 
were not doing this out of any whim or whimsy were doing 
it to save a species robinson said 
well face next year with more knowledge and experience than 
ever before said lisa stevens manager in charge of the zoos 
panda house 
as her human handlers recounted linglings latest travails at a 
news conference sunday the blackandwhite animal sat in her nest 
cradling apples put there in place of her missing baby 
the tiny cub weighing only 31 ounces was born prematurely 
friday at the national zoo and taken from its 250pound mother six 
hours later because of concern of infection 
zoo officials said the cub first began showing signs of strength 
but then weakened despite aroundtheclock efforts by zoo 
veterinarians and pediatric experts enlisted from nearby childrens 
hospital 
the cub was placed in an incubator fed a special formula through 
a tube into its stomach and given antibiotics to fight the 
infection officials said 
every effort was made to pull this cub through its illness 
said robinson at one point when zoo officials managed to separate 
the cub from a sedated mother he recalled i thought wed won 
without human aid the baby would have died well before it did 
the infection would have run away with it he said 
