<TEXT>
the treasury department has new evidence that a 
large number of americans living abroad cheat on their taxes and a 
new way to track the culprits 
if a sample studied by bryan l musselman of the internal revenue 
service is correct hundreds of thousands of americans living in 
other countries are not filing the tax returns that the law requires 
musselman did not estimate the loss to the treasury but in 1986 
the general accounting office which makes audits for congress 
estimated it at 620 million to 2 billion a year 
the gao said billions more are lost because americans at home 
make money in other countries and fail to report it 
earned income up to 70000 a year is exempt from us income tax 
for us citizens living abroad but they are still supposed to file 
returns and pay taxes on earned income above that level and on any 
unearned income such as interest 
musselmans report appears in this months treasury department 
volume 1989 update an analysis of statistics and trends 
in 1988 musselman began getting data from the state department 
under a new law on american citizens who apply for new passports 
from us consulates in other countries there were 73000 in the 
first year of operations he assumed that these are americans who 
live for a considerable time outside the united states american 
adults who go abroad need new passports every 10 years those under 
18 need one every five years 
revenue officials are matching the names from the state 
department against their master file to see who is filing tax 
returns and who is not 
no accurate data exist for the number of americans who live 
abroad and are not employed by the us government musselman 
wrote 
he estimated that 3 million americans were living abroad last 
year including about 750000 in the armed services for 1986 the 
internal revenue service got 264000 returns from addresses in other 
countries if it had received returns from abroad in the same 
proportion as in the united states there would have been about 12 
million 
its a bleak picture so far as tax collection is concerned 
musselman said in an interview 
many business people say it puts the united states at a 
disadvantage to collect taxes from its citizens abroad they say it 
encourages american companies in other countries to hire 
nonamericans 
i dont know of a single major industrial country europe or 
japan that taxes the earnings of its citizens when they reside 
abroad said bruce reynolds a tax partner with the international 
accounting firm touche ross and co 
the united states requires all but the poorest citizens to report 
their incomes wherever they live an unmarried person must report 
anything over 5100 a year 
if the income is earned americans overseas only have to pay 
taxes when a salary amounts to more than 70000 the military like 
other us government employees are not entitled to the exemption 
unearned income such as payments from stocks bonds real estate 
or other investments is all taxable whether americans get it in the 
united states or other countries though taxes paid to other 
countries can be deducted from american tax bills musselman said 
some of his figures give reason to think that a lot of the 
unreported income is unearned 
musselman studied a sample of 615 names he got from the state 
department and compared those with tax returns 
we can be 95 percent certain that the actual nonfiling rate is 
between 515 percent to 667 percent he said 
that would mean that one in every two or three americans living 
abroad did not send in returns he pointed out that this comes close 
to a figure from the general accounting office that 61 percent are 
nonfilers 
</TEXT>
