<TEXT>
strikers silenced factories stores and public 
transportation in azerbaijan on monday in a bid to regain their 
republics control of a region disputed with neighboring armenia 
in a separate ethnic dispute in the republic of moldavia 
russianspeaking workers stayed away from their jobs at about 200 
factories and offices to protest a law making moldavian the official 
language 
the strikes underscore the variety and severity of ethnic 
problems facing president mikhail s gorbachev and the countrys 
communist leadership 
the communist party central committee is scheduled to meet in 
early september to debate a new approach to relations among the 
soviet unions more than 100 ethnic groups 
the evening television news devoted its first 15 minutes monday 
to reports from moldavia which borders romania and two baltic 
republics lithuania and latvia 
popular movements in the baltic area are pressing for more 
autonomy from moscow and some activists there are pushing for 
secession 
mondays walkout in azerbaijan a mainly moslem republic on the 
caspian sea was called by the local peoples front political 
movement 
the strike committee claimed 95 percent of factories in the 
capital of baku a city with 17 million residents were shut by the 
strike and that freight trains were halted throughout the republic 
said nazim ragimov an independent journalist 
he said that number included about 200 factories but he had no 
figure for the number of people on strike ragimov was contacted by 
telephone 
editors at the official azerinform news agency said some 
employees went to their factories and offices but many did not work 
another editor reported the strike partly idled a major oil refining 
and processing center on the caspian coast 
food stores were the only shops open in baku izmail agayev head 
of the azerbaijan foreign ministrys information department said 
some bus and streetcar drivers also walked out 
he did not estimate how many people were on strike 
the peoples front has made several demands including the recall 
of representatives to the national congress of peoples deputies 
who they say were chosen in fraudulent balloting and did nothing in 
the parliaments first session 
they also demand that azerbaijan reassert control over 
nagornokarabakh a mountainous enclave it is 75 percent ethnic 
armenian although it lies in azerbaijan 
armenia wants to annex it and the kremlin has put it under 
direct rule to try to end the dispute 
the dispute has killed 100 people and forced hundreds of 
thousands to flee their homes 
krasnaya zvezda the defense ministry newspaper said sunday that 
tensions between armenia and azerbaijan are like gunpowder and 
that nagornokarabakh is on the verge of civil war 
the strikes in predominantly russiaspeaking regions of moldavia 
which began late last month continued monday when workers rejected 
a language compromise worked out in the republics supreme soviet 
legislature the compromise made moldavian the official language but 
did not impose it as the language that must be used by all ethnic 
groups 
strikers demand that the republics 42 million people 64 
percent of whom are ethnic moldavians have two official languages 
russian and moldavian 
