<DOCNO> AP890904-0112 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the great montana centennial cattle drive 
began monday in the golden light of sunrise as the lead longhorns 
crested a ridge in single file and then all 2700 animals formed an 
undulating bawling river of beef 
the sixday 60mile journey from this small community on the 
high plains of eastern montana to the stockyards of billings is the 
largest spectacle in montanas yearlong celebration of its birthday 
as a state 
the cattle herded by a band of 105 drovers was joined south of 
here by a contingent of about 300 covered wagons and 3000 riders 
prepared to spend the next week on the trail 
shortly before daybreak the cattle were headed up east of town 
along the musselshell river where they had been bedded down 
overnight 
as the sun broke over the horizon and lightened the clear sky 
the first longhorns trotted over the hill steam jetted from the 
nostrils of cows and horses in the crisp air and the cattle kicked 
up a haze of dust that drifted through the morning light 
whistling and whooping drovers in bright yellow slickers and 
waving lassos and bullwhips urged the complaining reluctant herd 
southward into a small canyon and between fields of brilliant green 
alfalfa 
from there the cattle were moved onto open range 
at late morning cheers greeted the sight of huge longhorns being 
herded through roundup leading the miles of wagons and riders 
toward their rendezvous with the main herd 
stomping and snorting in confusion one group of the animals 
turned onto main street where they were met with thousands of 
spectators lining the milelong route the crowd shied away from the 
steers each standing about six feet tall with horns spanning as 
much as five feet 
the people cheered and applauded many of the riders and wagons 
and cheered and rose to their feet hands over their hearts when 
the first of several flags finally appeared in the parade column 
riders on horseback and in wagons took on the appearance of their 
old west forerunners except in their desire to record the event 
many trained their video cameras on the other wagons and the crowd 
the first day of the cattle drive was marred by only one serious 
injury 
buck draper a cook from colorado springs colo suffered a hip 
injury when his horse reared over backwards and fell on him said 
musselshell county sheriff brian neidhardt he was flown by 
helicopter to a billings hospital 
the recreation of an old west drive will climax with another 
parade when the cattle arrive in billings on saturday 
on the trail the horse and wagon riders will eat catered meals 
and be entertained nightly by countrywestern performers 
trucks will bring 200000 gallons of water and 70 tons of hay 
each day to the animals 
montanas erractic endofsummer weather which can range from 
driving rain to broiling heat remains the greatest threat to the 
drive forecasts call for rain and cooler temperatures for most of 
the week 
</TEXT>
