<TEXT>
two newspapers that identified a source after 
promising confidentiality must pay 200000 in compensatory damages 
but not the 500000 in punitive damages also awarded by a jury the 
state court of appeals said in a ruling released tuesday 
first amendment guarantees of freedom of the press do not protect 
the star tribune and the st paul pioneer press dispatch from 
liability under contract laws in this case the oral contracts of 
reporters confidentiality promises a threejudge panel said in 
upholding the compensatory damages 
in the ruling to be filed tuesday in st paul the judges 
rejected public relations man dan cohens claim of misrepresentation 
by the newspapers and said he is not entitled to punitive damages 
awarded by a hennepin county jury 
the court also rejected the star tribunes contention that the 
closing argument for cohen was so inflammatory that a new trial is 
required the damages payment is to be shared by the newspapers 
the court made the ruling available to the news media with the 
proviso that the parties involved not be contacted for comment 
before 830 am tuesday 
judge gary crippen in a partial dissent said the entire 
700000 award should be overturned because the case involves the 
exercise of the coercive power of the state to punish the choice of 
the private press to publish 
in a statement issued for release tuesday however star tribune 
executive editor joel r kramer said the paper is pleased with the 
courts unanimous decision on punitive damages and heartened by 
crippens partial dissent 
we are disappointed with the court majoritys ruling that 
contract law applies in this case and supersedes first amendment 
protections he said no decision on whether to appeal has been 
made he said 
the case concerns a revelation during the 1982 gubernatorial 
campaign that marlene johnson a democratic farmer labor candidate 
for lieutenant governor had been arrested on shoplifting charges 
several years earlier 
cohen who worked for independentrepublican gubernatorial 
candidate wheelock whitney provided the information on the 
condition that he not be identified as the source 
reporters for the two newspapers gave that assurance but their 
editors ordered that cohens name be published because they argued 
the public had the right to know that the information came from the 
whitney campaign 
johnon went on to win the election but cohen sued claiming that 
he lost his advertising agency job because the newspapers breached 
an oral contract 
the appeals court agreed saying an oral contract between a 
source and a reporter is no different from any other contract 
any first amendment rights the newspapers might have had to 
publish the sources name were waived when the reporters made the 
confidentiality pledge the opinion said 
the newspapers argument that the public had the right to 
information about the source was valid the court said to provide a 
context of the sources credibility and motivations but that 
doesnt mean the papers had to use cohens name the opinion said 
cohen based his claim of misrepresentation in part on a legal 
inference that editors never intended to keep the reporters 
promises of confidentiality in addition he claimed that the 
reporters concealed that they had no authority to bind the 
newspapers to their promise 
the appeals court said cohen could not legally infer that the 
editors didnt intend to keep the promise the court also noted that 
no witness could recall a previous instance when a reporters 
confidentiality promise was vetoed by an editor at either paper 
because it was the newspapers practice to honor their 
reporters promises of confidentiality the reporters did not by 
omission misrepresent their authority the court said in rejecting 
punitive damages in the misrepresentation claim 
judge marianne short who wrote the decision defended the ruling 
against potential complaints that its effect would be to restrict 
the media and limit public access to information 
were we not to enforce the newspapers promises of 
confidentiality confidential sources would have no legal recourse 
against unscrupulous reporters or editors she said 
ultimately news sources could dry up resulting in less 
newsworthy information to publish 
</TEXT>
