<TEXT>
former gov pat brown once let a deathrow 
inmate die to get a bill through the legislature and hes still 
haunted by the lifeanddeath power he held over 59 prisoners 
brown emerges as an opponent of the death penalty in public 
justice private mercy the 163page memoir of his decisions to 
grant or withhold clemency from prisoners facing death sentences 
while he was governor from 195967 
it was an awesome ultimate power over the lives of others that 
no person or government should have or crave brown writes 
each decision took something out of me that nothing not family 
or work or hope for the future has ever been able to replace 
brown commuted 23 death sentences the most of any california 
governor he denied clemency in 36 other cases 
the decisions were some of the most agonizing he ever made brown 
said in the book he wrote with dick adler it was published last 
month by weidenfeld amp nicolson 
some of the 23 prisoners whose sentences brown commuted were 
released on parole one was later convicted of murder despite his 
opposition to capital punishment brown recalled after learning 
about the 1975 murder he stated he would have been willing to trade 
all 23 lives for the life of the killers victim 
there is a message for future governors particularly opponents 
of capital punishment the tension between justice and mercy 
may be impossible to resolve especially in a heated arena of 
political ambitions and public expectations 
the issue is far from academic in california which with more 
than 200 inmates has one the nations largests deathrow 
populations and is likely to begin executing the prisoners soon 
after a 22year respite 
the state put more than 500 people to death from 1851 to 1967 in 
1976 the us supreme court allowed states to resume executions 
but the california supreme court under liberal chief justice rose 
bird threw out many death sentences since a more conservative court 
took over after birds election defeat in 1986 state laws have 
changed to make executions easier 
in his book brown writes that he found the moral and political 
decisions became hopelessly entangled in the case of richard 
lindsey a drifter convicted of raping and murdering a 6yearold 
girl in a kern county farm labor camp in 1961 
as brown describes it he was seriously considering clemency for 
lindsey who though legally sane had been mentally disturbed for 
many years but the governor also sought legislative approval of a 
minimumwage law for migrant workers and he needed the vote of a 
kern county lawmaker who wanted lindsey dead 
by letting richard lindsey go to the gas chamber i was giving 
the victims parents and people like them a chance at a living 
wage brown writes lindsey died and the legislation passed 
brown criticizes some of his actions and appears to have been 
genuinely wrestling with two principles his personal opposition to 
capital punishment and his belief he was elected to uphold the law 
including the death penalty 
brown is less convincing in describing his decision not to 
commute the death sentence of caryl chessman convicted of a string 
of kidnappings and rapes who spent 12 years on death row before he 
was executed in may 1960 
brown said chessman was a nasty arrogant unrepentant man 
but probably did not deserve to die because he hadnt killed anyone 
brown admits his decision not to grant clemency was partly 
because widespread anger at chessman made that decision politically 
untenable 
brown concludes that the death penalty is unfair irrational and 
ineffective but that it will not be abolished until more people 
realize how inhumane it is 
for this reason he supports an initiative being circulated for 
californias june 1990 ballot to speed up court proceedings by 
narrowing defendants rights with speedier appeals the gas chamber 
soon would be operating two or three times a week brown said 
then he said people would begin to see the death penalty in 
all its naked ugliness 
</TEXT>
