<TEXT>
aaron buck buchwach former editor in chief 
of the honolulu advertiser and a colorful figure in hawaiis news 
industry for more than four decades died sunday he was 68 
buchwach apparently suffered a heart attack at his home said the 
advertisers editor at large george chaplin a close friend 
buchwach died at the queens medical center at 1147 pm a nursing 
supervisor said 
a native of portland ore buchwach began his journalism career 
in eugene as a sportswriter for the registerguard and graduated 
from the university of oregon with a degree in journalism in 1942 
he came to hawaii during world war ii and was city editor for the 
pacific edition of stars amp stripes he joined the advertiser in 1946 
and held the positions of reporter city editor managing editor 
executive editor and editor in chief 
as an advertiser reporter buchwach interviewed seven us 
presidents as well as gen douglas macarthur and adm chester 
nimitz he covered volcanoes tidal waves national politics and in 
1967 reported on the arabisraeli war 
he served a brief stint in public relations during the 1950s but 
returned to the newspaper buchwach retired from the morning 
newspaper in february and worked for an advertising agency 
he headed the honolulu press club for five terms and was a 
twoterm president of the hawaii chapter of the society of 
professional journalists 
buchwach is survived by his wife peggy seven children and four 
grandchildren 
