<TEXT>
hj heinz co subsidiary starkist foods 
announced a plan to fund research to reduce the number of dolphins 
killed in tuna fishing nets just days before animal rights activists 
plan to protest the companys alleged involvement in dolphin killing 
starkist spokesman erik bloemendaal said last weeks 
announcement of the research funds was unrelated to a protest 
scheduled to take place wednesday before heinzs annual meeting in 
pittsburgh 
todd steiner director of the save the dolphins project at earth 
island institute in san francisco which organized the protest 
called the research project a public relations scam 
the institute claims star kist purchases tuna caught by 
encirclement nets that each year needlessly kill 100000 dolphins 
the group said it targeted starkist because it is the worlds 
largest tuna processor 
heinz has studied the possibility of funding research by the 
world dolphin research society since the beginning of the year but 
had not determined all the details until recently bloemendaal said 
the research is intended to develop acoustic and electromagnetic 
signals to calm dolphins and guide them out of the nets 
the world dolphin research society is a nonprofit organization 
founded two years ago by the aspen research institute of aspen colo 
bloemendaal declined to say how much the company will spend for 
the research but called it a significant amount 
steiner said the research funds would be better spent designing 
alternative fishing methods he said 95 percent of all tuna is 
caught by methods that dont harm dolphins 
earth island institute organized a demonstration at the 1988 
heinz shareholders meeting and has asked consumers to boycott 
starkist tuna the boycott has not affected sales heinz 
spokeswoman debbie foster said 
heinz chairman jf anthony oreilly has said he sympathizes with 
animal rights groups but claims foreign fleets kill most of the 
dolphins boycotting starkist will not save any dolphins he told 
shareholders last year 
foreign fleets will simply sell their catch to other countries 
who have little or no concern regarding the dolphins oreilly 
said 
</TEXT>
