<TEXT>
consumer confidence dropped in august after 
rising steadily for several months according to a poll released 
today by a business group 
the conference boards consumer confidence index declined in 
august to 1147 a loss of almost six points for the month the 
group said 
a substantial share of the decline reflects consumers somewhat 
less positive assessment of current economic conditions the group 
said expectations for the future are down moderately while buying 
plans are mixed it said 
consumer confidence is important because of its impact on 
consumer spending which drives about twothirds of domestic 
economic activity 
although the level of consumer confidence is down it is still 
in the context of the surveys history reassuringly strong said 
fabian linden executive director of the conference boards consumer 
research center 
while one month is too brief a period on which to make a 
longterm judgment the magnitude of this months decline cannot be 
dismissed as inconsequential he said in a statement we must 
wait for at least another month to see whether this is the beginning 
of a trend 
only 27 percent of survey participants said that current economic 
conditions are good down from 316 percent a month earlier about 
31 percent said they believed jobs were plentiful down from about 
33 percent in july 
there was a modest decline from 186 percent to 172 percent in 
the number who expect more jobs to become available over the next 
six months about 25 percent of respondents believed that their 
families financial situation would improve a drop of about 2 
percent points from july 
automobile purchasing plans remained unchanged at 71 percent of 
respondents the percentage planning to buy a home declined to 35 
percent from 37 percent in july interest in buying a major 
appliance dropped to 271 percent from 305 percent 
the monthly survey covering 5000 us households is conducted 
for the new yorkbased group by national family opinion of toledo 
ohio 
</TEXT>
